{% extends "layout.html" %}

{% block title %}Common Gynecological Issues | Women's Health Hub{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
<div class="container py-5">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-8">
      <h1 class="mb-4">Common Gynecological Issues</h1>
      <p class="lead mb-4">Understanding common gynecological conditions, their symptoms, prevention strategies, and treatment options to help you advocate for your reproductive health.</p>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Menstrual Disorders</h5>
          
          <div class="accordion" id="menstrualAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingDysmenorrhea">
                <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseDysmenorrhea" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseDysmenorrhea">
                  Dysmenorrhea (Painful Periods)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseDysmenorrhea" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingDysmenorrhea" data-bs-parent="#menstrualAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Types:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Primary dysmenorrhea:</strong> Pain without underlying condition, usually begins with onset of periods</li>
                        <li><strong>Secondary dysmenorrhea:</strong> Pain caused by reproductive disorder (endometriosis, fibroids, etc.)</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Symptoms:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Cramping in lower abdomen, back, or thighs</li>
                        <li>Pain starting before or during menstruation</li>
                        <li>May include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, headache</li>
                        <li>Severity ranges from mild to debilitating</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Management:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Over-the-counter pain relievers (ibuprofen, naproxen)</li>
                        <li>Heat therapy (heating pad, warm bath)</li>
                        <li>Hormonal contraceptives to regulate hormones</li>
                        <li>Physical activity</li>
                        <li>Stress reduction</li>
                        <li>Dietary changes (reducing caffeine, salt)</li>
                        <li>Supplements (magnesium, vitamin B1, fish oil)</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-info">
                        <h6>When to Seek Help:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Pain that doesn't improve with over-the-counter medication</li>
                          <li>Pain that interferes with daily activities</li>
                          <li>New or worsening pain after age 25</li>
                          <li>Pain at times other than menstruation</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingMenorrhagia">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseMenorrhagia" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseMenorrhagia">
                  Menorrhagia (Heavy Menstrual Bleeding)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseMenorrhagia" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingMenorrhagia" data-bs-parent="#menstrualAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>Abnormally heavy or prolonged menstrual bleeding, typically:</p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Needing to change menstrual products every hour</li>
                        <li>Passing large blood clots</li>
                        <li>Bleeding lasting more than 7 days</li>
                        <li>Need to use double protection</li>
                        <li>Bleeding that interferes with daily activities</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Potential Causes:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Hormonal imbalance</li>
                        <li>Uterine fibroids</li>
                        <li>Polyps</li>
                        <li>Adenomyosis</li>
                        <li>Intrauterine devices (IUDs)</li>
                        <li>Bleeding disorders</li>
                        <li>Thyroid disorders</li>
                        <li>Medications (anticoagulants)</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Treatment Options:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Iron supplements (for anemia)</li>
                        <li>Hormonal birth control (pills, patch, ring, hormonal IUD)</li>
                        <li>Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)</li>
                        <li>Tranexamic acid during menstruation</li>
                        <li>Treatment of underlying cause (if identified)</li>
                        <li>Surgical options for severe cases (endometrial ablation, hysterectomy)</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-warning">
                        <h6>When to Seek Help:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Soaking through one or more tampons/pads per hour</li>
                          <li>Bleeding that lasts longer than 7 days</li>
                          <li>Passing clots larger than a quarter</li>
                          <li>Feeling dizzy or fatigued</li>
                          <li>Symptoms of anemia (shortness of breath, fatigue)</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingIrregular">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseIrregular" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseIrregular">
                  Irregular Periods
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseIrregular" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingIrregular" data-bs-parent="#menstrualAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>Menstrual cycles that vary in length or frequency, including:</p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Cycles shorter than 21 days or longer than 35 days</li>
                        <li>Unpredictable timing</li>
                        <li>Missed periods</li>
                        <li>Variable flow intensity</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Common Causes:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Stress and lifestyle factors</li>
                        <li>Significant weight changes</li>
                        <li>Excessive exercise</li>
                        <li>Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)</li>
                        <li>Thyroid disorders</li>
                        <li>Perimenopause</li>
                        <li>Hormonal contraception (especially when starting or stopping)</li>
                        <li>Pregnancy or breastfeeding</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Management:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Tracking cycles to identify patterns</li>
                        <li>Addressing lifestyle factors (stress, weight, exercise)</li>
                        <li>Hormonal birth control to regulate cycles</li>
                        <li>Treatment of underlying conditions</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-info">
                        <h6>Normal Variation:</h6>
                        <p>Slight irregularity is common at certain life stages:</p>
                        <ul>
                          <li>After menarche (first periods)</li>
                          <li>After pregnancy and during breastfeeding</li>
                          <li>During perimenopause (years before menopause)</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingPMS">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapsePMS" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapsePMS">
                  PMS & PMDD
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapsePMS" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingPMS" data-bs-parent="#menstrualAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-12">
                      <h6>Premenstrual Syndrome (PMS):</h6>
                      <p>A collection of physical and emotional symptoms occurring 1-2 weeks before menstruation that resolve with the onset of period.</p>
                      
                      <p><strong>Common PMS symptoms:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Physical:</strong> Bloating, breast tenderness, acne, headaches, food cravings</li>
                        <li><strong>Emotional:</strong> Irritability, mood swings, fatigue, difficulty concentrating</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <p><strong>PMS management:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Regular exercise</li>
                        <li>Adequate sleep</li>
                        <li>Stress reduction techniques</li>
                        <li>Dietary changes (reducing salt, sugar, caffeine, alcohol)</li>
                        <li>Calcium supplements (1200mg daily)</li>
                        <li>Over-the-counter pain relievers</li>
                        <li>Hormonal birth control</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  
                  <div class="row mt-3">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Premenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD):</h6>
                      <p>A more severe form of PMS affecting 3-8% of women, characterized by intense emotional and physical symptoms that significantly interfere with daily life.</p>
                      
                      <p><strong>PMDD symptoms:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Severe depression, hopelessness, or self-deprecating thoughts</li>
                        <li>Intense anxiety or tension</li>
                        <li>Extreme mood swings, irritability, or anger</li>
                        <li>Difficulty concentrating</li>
                        <li>Fatigue or low energy</li>
                        <li>Food cravings or binge eating</li>
                        <li>Sleep problems</li>
                        <li>Feeling overwhelmed or out of control</li>
                        <li>Physical symptoms (breast tenderness, bloating, headaches)</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <p><strong>PMDD treatment:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Antidepressants (especially SSRIs)</li>
                        <li>Hormonal treatments (continuous birth control)</li>
                        <li>Cognitive behavioral therapy</li>
                        <li>Lifestyle modifications (as with PMS)</li>
                        <li>Vitamin B6, calcium, magnesium supplements</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-danger">
                        <h6>When to Seek Help for PMDD:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Suicidal thoughts</li>
                          <li>Symptoms interfering with relationships or work</li>
                          <li>Depression that doesn't improve after period starts</li>
                          <li>Inability to manage symptoms with lifestyle changes</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Reproductive Tract Conditions</h5>
          
          <div class="accordion" id="reproductiveAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingEndometriosis">
                <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseEndometriosis" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseEndometriosis">
                  Endometriosis
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseEndometriosis" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingEndometriosis" data-bs-parent="#reproductiveAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>A condition where tissue similar to the uterine lining (endometrium) grows outside the uterus, commonly on ovaries, fallopian tubes, and pelvic tissue.</p>
                      
                      <h6>Symptoms:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Severe pelvic pain, especially during periods</li>
                        <li>Pain during intercourse</li>
                        <li>Pain with bowel movements or urination (especially during periods)</li>
                        <li>Excessive bleeding (heavy periods or bleeding between periods)</li>
                        <li>Infertility</li>
                        <li>Fatigue, diarrhea, constipation, bloating, nausea</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Diagnosis:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Clinical evaluation of symptoms</li>
                        <li>Pelvic exam</li>
                        <li>Ultrasound</li>
                        <li>Laparoscopy (surgical procedure for definitive diagnosis)</li>
                        <li>MRI (in some cases)</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Treatment Options:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Pain medications (NSAIDs)</li>
                        <li>Hormonal contraceptives (pills, patches, rings)</li>
                        <li>Hormonal therapies (GnRH agonists, progestins)</li>
                        <li>Conservative surgery (removal of endometrial tissue while preserving reproductive organs)</li>
                        <li>Hysterectomy with removal of ovaries (in severe cases)</li>
                        <li>Complementary approaches (acupuncture, diet modifications)</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-info">
                        <h6>Key Facts:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Affects approximately 10% of reproductive-age women</li>
                          <li>Often takes 7-10 years from symptom onset to diagnosis</li>
                          <li>Leading cause of pelvic pain and a major cause of infertility</li>
                          <li>Symptoms may improve during pregnancy and resolve after menopause</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingPCOS">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapsePCOS" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapsePCOS">
                  Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapsePCOS" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingPCOS" data-bs-parent="#reproductiveAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>A hormonal disorder characterized by elevated androgens (male hormones), irregular periods, and small fluid-filled sacs (follicles) in the ovaries.</p>
                      
                      <h6>Symptoms:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Irregular or absent periods</li>
                        <li>Excessive facial and body hair (hirsutism)</li>
                        <li>Acne</li>
                        <li>Weight gain or difficulty losing weight</li>
                        <li>Thinning hair or hair loss (male-pattern baldness)</li>
                        <li>Skin tags</li>
                        <li>Darkening of skin in creases (neck, groin, under breasts)</li>
                        <li>Infertility or difficulty conceiving</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Diagnosis:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Medical history and physical examination</li>
                        <li>Pelvic ultrasound to visualize ovaries</li>
                        <li>Blood tests to measure hormone levels</li>
                        <li>Exclusion of other conditions with similar symptoms</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Management:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Lifestyle modifications (diet, exercise, weight management)</li>
                        <li>Hormonal birth control to regulate periods</li>
                        <li>Anti-androgen medications to reduce symptoms like acne and hair growth</li>
                        <li>Metformin to improve insulin sensitivity</li>
                        <li>Fertility treatments when pregnancy is desired</li>
                        <li>Treatment of specific symptoms (hair removal, acne treatment)</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-warning">
                        <h6>Long-term Health Considerations:</h6>
                        <p>Women with PCOS have increased risk of:</p>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Type 2 diabetes</li>
                          <li>Heart disease</li>
                          <li>High blood pressure</li>
                          <li>Endometrial cancer</li>
                          <li>Sleep apnea</li>
                          <li>Depression and anxiety</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>Regular monitoring and preventive care are important.</p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFibroids">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFibroids" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFibroids">
                  Uterine Fibroids
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseFibroids" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFibroids" data-bs-parent="#reproductiveAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>Noncancerous growths of the uterus that often appear during childbearing years. They range from tiny seedlings to bulky masses that can distort the uterus.</p>
                      
                      <h6>Types:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Intramural:</strong> Within the muscular uterine wall</li>
                        <li><strong>Subserosal:</strong> Outside the uterus, projecting into the pelvic cavity</li>
                        <li><strong>Submucosal:</strong> Just under the inner lining, protruding into the uterine cavity</li>
                        <li><strong>Pedunculated:</strong> Attached to the uterus by a stem-like structure</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Symptoms:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Heavy menstrual bleeding</li>
                        <li>Prolonged periods</li>
                        <li>Pelvic pressure or pain</li>
                        <li>Frequent urination</li>
                        <li>Difficulty emptying bladder</li>
                        <li>Constipation</li>
                        <li>Backache or leg pain</li>
                        <li>Pain during intercourse</li>
                      </ul>
                      <p><em>Note: Many women with fibroids have no symptoms at all.</em></p>
                      
                      <h6>Treatment Options:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Watchful waiting:</strong> For asymptomatic fibroids</li>
                        <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Pain relievers, hormonal therapy, GnRH agonists</li>
                        <li><strong>Noninvasive procedures:</strong> MRI-guided focused ultrasound</li>
                        <li><strong>Minimally invasive procedures:</strong> Uterine artery embolization, myomectomy, endometrial ablation</li>
                        <li><strong>Traditional surgery:</strong> Hysterectomy (when other treatments fail or are unsuitable)</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-info">
                        <h6>Key Facts:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Extremely common - affecting up to 80% of women by age 50</li>
                          <li>More common in African American women</li>
                          <li>Usually not associated with increased risk of uterine cancer</li>
                          <li>Often shrink after menopause</li>
                          <li>May grow rapidly during pregnancy</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingOvarianCysts">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseOvarianCysts" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseOvarianCysts">
                  Ovarian Cysts
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseOvarianCysts" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingOvarianCysts" data-bs-parent="#reproductiveAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>Fluid-filled sacs that develop on or within the ovaries.</p>
                      
                      <h6>Types:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Functional cysts:</strong>
                          <ul>
                            <li><em>Follicular cysts:</em> Form when a follicle doesn't release an egg and continues growing</li>
                            <li><em>Corpus luteum cysts:</em> Form when the follicle releases an egg but then reseals and fills with fluid</li>
                          </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Other types:</strong>
                          <ul>
                            <li><em>Dermoid cysts:</em> Contain tissue (hair, skin, teeth)</li>
                            <li><em>Cystadenomas:</em> Develop from ovarian tissue</li>
                            <li><em>Endometriomas:</em> From endometriosis affecting the ovaries</li>
                          </ul>
                        </li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Symptoms:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Often asymptomatic</li>
                        <li>Pelvic pain or pressure</li>
                        <li>Bloating or swelling</li>
                        <li>Painful intercourse</li>
                        <li>Changes in menstrual patterns</li>
                        <li>Urinary or bowel symptoms (frequency, difficulty)</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Treatment Approaches:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Watchful waiting:</strong> For small, asymptomatic cysts</li>
                        <li><strong>Birth control pills:</strong> To prevent new cysts</li>
                        <li><strong>Surgery:</strong> For large, painful, or suspicious cysts</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-danger">
                        <h6>Warning Signs:</h6>
                        <p>Seek immediate medical attention for:</p>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Sudden, severe abdominal or pelvic pain</li>
                          <li>Pain with fever or vomiting</li>
                          <li>Dizziness, weakness, rapid breathing</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>These could indicate cyst rupture or ovarian torsion (twisting), which are medical emergencies.</p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Infectious Conditions</h5>
          
          <div class="accordion" id="infectiousAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingVaginitis">
                <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseVaginitis" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseVaginitis">
                  Vaginitis
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseVaginitis" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingVaginitis" data-bs-parent="#infectiousAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p>Vaginitis refers to various vaginal inflammations. The three most common types are:</p>
                  
                  <h6 class="mt-3">Yeast Infections (Candidiasis)</h6>
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-6">
                      <p><strong>Symptoms:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Thick, white, odorless discharge (cottage cheese-like)</li>
                        <li>Itching and irritation</li>
                        <li>Burning during urination or intercourse</li>
                        <li>Redness and swelling of the vulva</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-6">
                      <p><strong>Treatment:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Over-the-counter antifungal creams, ointments, tablets</li>
                        <li>Prescription oral antifungal medications</li>
                        <li>Boric acid suppositories for recurring infections</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  
                  <h6 class="mt-3">Bacterial Vaginosis (BV)</h6>
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-6">
                      <p><strong>Symptoms:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Thin, gray or white discharge</li>
                        <li>Fishy odor, especially after intercourse</li>
                        <li>Burning during urination</li>
                        <li>Itching</li>
                        <li>Many women have no symptoms</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-6">
                      <p><strong>Treatment:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Prescription antibiotics (oral or vaginal)</li>
                        <li>Treatment of sexual partners usually not necessary</li>
                        <li>Probiotics may help prevent recurrence</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  
                  <h6 class="mt-3">Trichomoniasis</h6>
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-6">
                      <p><strong>Symptoms:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Greenish-yellow, frothy discharge</li>
                        <li>Strong odor</li>
                        <li>Genital itching and redness</li>
                        <li>Discomfort during intercourse and urination</li>
                        <li>Up to 70% may have no symptoms</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-6">
                      <p><strong>Treatment:</strong></p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Prescription oral antibiotics (usually metronidazole or tinidazole)</li>
                        <li>Both partners need treatment (sexually transmitted)</li>
                        <li>Avoid alcohol during treatment and for 24-72 hours after</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  
                  <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
                    <h6>Prevention Strategies for Vaginal Infections:</h6>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Avoid douching</li>
                      <li>Use unscented soaps and hygiene products</li>
                      <li>Wipe from front to back after using the toilet</li>
                      <li>Wear cotton underwear and loose-fitting clothing</li>
                      <li>Change out of wet clothes promptly</li>
                      <li>Practice safer sex</li>
                      <li>Consider probiotics (especially after antibiotics)</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingPID">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapsePID" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapsePID">
                  Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapsePID" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingPID" data-bs-parent="#infectiousAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>An infection of the female reproductive organs, usually caused by bacteria ascending from the vagina and cervix to the upper reproductive tract.</p>
                      
                      <h6>Causes:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Most commonly caused by untreated sexually transmitted infections (STIs), especially gonorrhea and chlamydia</li>
                        <li>Can also develop from normal vaginal bacteria</li>
                        <li>Risk increases with multiple sexual partners, history of STIs, douching, and recent IUD insertion</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Symptoms:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Lower abdominal pain (can be mild to severe)</li>
                        <li>Fever</li>
                        <li>Unusual vaginal discharge with unpleasant odor</li>
                        <li>Pain during intercourse</li>
                        <li>Painful urination</li>
                        <li>Irregular menstrual bleeding</li>
                        <li>May have no symptoms (especially with chlamydia)</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Diagnosis:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Physical examination</li>
                        <li>Cervical cultures for STI testing</li>
                        <li>Blood tests</li>
                        <li>Ultrasound</li>
                        <li>Endometrial biopsy (rarely)</li>
                        <li>Laparoscopy (in severe cases)</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Treatment:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Antibiotics (often a combination to cover various bacteria)</li>
                        <li>Treatment of sexual partners</li>
                        <li>Hospitalization for severe cases</li>
                        <li>Surgery (rarely) for abscesses or severe complications</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-warning">
                        <h6>Potential Complications:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Chronic pelvic pain</li>
                          <li>Scarring of fallopian tubes</li>
                          <li>Infertility (affects about 1 in 10 women with PID)</li>
                          <li>Ectopic pregnancy</li>
                          <li>Tubo-ovarian abscess</li>
                          <li>Increased risk of future episodes</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                      
                      <div class="alert alert-danger mt-3">
                        <h6>When to Seek Emergency Care:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Severe pain in lower abdomen</li>
                          <li>Nausea and vomiting</li>
                          <li>High fever (over 101°F/38.3°C)</li>
                          <li>Foul vaginal discharge</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingUTI">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseUTI" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseUTI">
                  Urinary Tract Infections (UTIs)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseUTI" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingUTI" data-bs-parent="#infectiousAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>Infection in any part of the urinary system (kidneys, ureters, bladder, urethra), most commonly affecting the lower urinary tract (bladder and urethra).</p>
                      
                      <h6>Why Women Are More Vulnerable:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Shorter urethra (makes it easier for bacteria to reach bladder)</li>
                        <li>Proximity of urethra to vagina and rectum</li>
                        <li>Hormonal changes (especially during menopause)</li>
                        <li>Sexual activity</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Symptoms:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Strong, persistent urge to urinate</li>
                        <li>Burning sensation when urinating</li>
                        <li>Passing frequent, small amounts of urine</li>
                        <li>Cloudy, strong-smelling urine</li>
                        <li>Pelvic pain (particularly in center of pelvis)</li>
                        <li>Blood in urine</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Treatment:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Antibiotics (type and duration depend on severity)</li>
                        <li>Pain medication for discomfort</li>
                        <li>Increased fluid intake</li>
                        <li>Avoid irritants (caffeine, alcohol) until infection resolves</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Prevention:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Stay hydrated</li>
                        <li>Urinate after sexual activity</li>
                        <li>Wipe from front to back</li>
                        <li>Avoid potentially irritating feminine products</li>
                        <li>Consider cranberry products (some evidence for prevention)</li>
                        <li>Wear breathable, cotton underwear</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-warning">
                        <h6>Recurrent UTIs:</h6>
                        <p>Some women experience frequent UTIs (3 or more per year). Management may include:</p>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Low-dose prophylactic antibiotics</li>
                          <li>Post-intercourse antibiotic single dose</li>
                          <li>Self-start antibiotic therapy</li>
                          <li>Vaginal estrogen in postmenopausal women</li>
                          <li>Evaluation for anatomical abnormalities</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                      
                      <div class="alert alert-danger mt-3">
                        <h6>Warning Signs of Kidney Infection:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>High fever</li>
                          <li>Back or side (flank) pain</li>
                          <li>Nausea and vomiting</li>
                          <li>Shaking and chills</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>Seek immediate medical attention as kidney infections can be serious and require prompt treatment.</p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Pelvic Floor Disorders</h5>
          
          <div class="accordion" id="pelvicFloorAccordion">
