            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingIncontinence">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseIncontinence" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseIncontinence">
                  Urinary Incontinence
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseIncontinence" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingIncontinence" data-bs-parent="#pelvicFloorAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-12">
                      <h6>Types of Urinary Incontinence:</h6>
                      
                      <div class="row mt-3">
                        <div class="col-md-6">
                          <div class="card h-100">
                            <div class="card-body">
                              <h6 class="card-title">Stress Incontinence</h6>
                              <p><strong>Description:</strong> Leakage of urine during activities that put pressure on the bladder</p>
                              <p><strong>Triggers:</strong> Coughing, sneezing, laughing, exercising, lifting heavy objects</p>
                              <p><strong>Cause:</strong> Weakened pelvic floor muscles or damaged urethral sphincter</p>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-md-6">
                          <div class="card h-100">
                            <div class="card-body">
                              <h6 class="card-title">Urge Incontinence</h6>
                              <p><strong>Description:</strong> Sudden, intense urge to urinate followed by involuntary loss of urine</p>
                              <p><strong>Triggers:</strong> Sound of running water, change in position, anxiety</p>
                              <p><strong>Cause:</strong> Overactive bladder muscles or nerve signaling problems</p>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      
                      <div class="row mt-3">
                        <div class="col-md-6">
                          <div class="card h-100">
                            <div class="card-body">
                              <h6 class="card-title">Mixed Incontinence</h6>
                              <p><strong>Description:</strong> Combination of stress and urge incontinence</p>
                              <p><strong>Common in:</strong> Older women and those who have had multiple childbirths</p>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-md-6">
                          <div class="card h-100">
                            <div class="card-body">
                              <h6 class="card-title">Overflow Incontinence</h6>
                              <p><strong>Description:</strong> Frequent or constant dribbling due to bladder not emptying completely</p>
                              <p><strong>Cause:</strong> Blocked urethra or bladder muscle weakness</p>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      
                      <h6 class="mt-4">Treatment Options:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Pelvic floor exercises (Kegels):</strong> Strengthen muscles supporting the bladder</li>
                        <li><strong>Bladder training:</strong> Techniques to increase time between voiding</li>
                        <li><strong>Lifestyle changes:</strong> Weight loss, dietary modifications (reducing caffeine, alcohol), fluid management</li>
                        <li><strong>Medications:</strong> For urge incontinence (anticholinergics, beta-3 agonists)</li>
                        <li><strong>Devices:</strong> Pessaries, urethral inserts</li>
                        <li><strong>Procedures:</strong> Botox injections, nerve stimulation</li>
                        <li><strong>Surgery:</strong> Sling procedures, bladder neck suspension</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingProlapse">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseProlapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseProlapse">
                  Pelvic Organ Prolapse
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseProlapse" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingProlapse" data-bs-parent="#pelvicFloorAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>A condition where one or more pelvic organs descend from their normal position and bulge into the vagina due to weakened support structures.</p>
                      
                      <h6>Types:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Cystocele:</strong> Bladder drops into vagina (most common)</li>
                        <li><strong>Rectocele:</strong> Rectum bulges into vagina</li>
                        <li><strong>Uterine prolapse:</strong> Uterus descends into vagina</li>
                        <li><strong>Vaginal vault prolapse:</strong> Top of vagina sags down (after hysterectomy)</li>
                        <li><strong>Enterocele:</strong> Small intestine bulges into vagina</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Symptoms:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Sensation of pressure or fullness in pelvic area</li>
                        <li>Tissue bulging out of vagina</li>
                        <li>Difficulty emptying bladder or bowels</li>
                        <li>Low back pain that eases when lying down</li>
                        <li>Sexual difficulties</li>
                        <li>Urinary or fecal incontinence</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Treatment Options:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Non-surgical:</strong>
                          <ul>
                            <li>Pelvic floor exercises</li>
                            <li>Pessary (supportive device placed in vagina)</li>
                            <li>Lifestyle modifications (weight management, avoiding heavy lifting)</li>
                          </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Surgical:</strong>
                          <ul>
                            <li>Reconstructive surgery to repair weakened tissues</li>
                            <li>Obliterative surgery (closes the vaginal canal - for women not sexually active)</li>
                          </ul>
                        </li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-info">
                        <h6>Severity Grades:</h6>
                        <p>Prolapse is typically graded from 0-4:</p>
                        <ul>
                          <li><strong>Grade 0:</strong> No prolapse</li>
                          <li><strong>Grade 1:</strong> Descent halfway to hymen</li>
                          <li><strong>Grade 2:</strong> Descent to hymen</li>
                          <li><strong>Grade 3:</strong> Descent beyond hymen</li>
                          <li><strong>Grade 4:</strong> Complete eversion (organ completely outside)</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingPelvicPain">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapsePelvicPain" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapsePelvicPain">
                  Chronic Pelvic Pain
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapsePelvicPain" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingPelvicPain" data-bs-parent="#pelvicFloorAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8">
                      <h6>Definition:</h6>
                      <p>Pain in the pelvic region that persists for 6 months or longer, affecting daily activities and quality of life.</p>
                      
                      <h6>Potential Causes:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Gynecological conditions:</strong> Endometriosis, adenomyosis, fibroids, ovarian cysts</li>
                        <li><strong>Musculoskeletal issues:</strong> Pelvic floor muscle dysfunction, trigger points, joint instability</li>
                        <li><strong>Urological disorders:</strong> Interstitial cystitis, recurring UTIs</li>
                        <li><strong>Gastrointestinal problems:</strong> Irritable bowel syndrome, inflammatory bowel disease</li>
                        <li><strong>Nerve conditions:</strong> Pudendal neuralgia, nerve entrapment</li>
                        <li><strong>Psychological factors:</strong> Depression, anxiety, history of abuse (can exacerbate pain)</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Diagnosis:</h6>
                      <p>Often requires multidisciplinary approach, including:</p>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Detailed history and physical examination</li>
                        <li>Pelvic floor muscle assessment</li>
                        <li>Imaging studies (ultrasound, MRI)</li>
                        <li>Laparoscopy (in some cases)</li>
                        <li>Ruling out other conditions</li>
                      </ul>
                      
                      <h6>Treatment Approaches:</h6>
                      <ul>
                        <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Pain relievers, hormone therapy, antidepressants (for pain modulation)</li>
                        <li><strong>Physical therapy:</strong> Pelvic floor rehabilitation, trigger point release</li>
                        <li><strong>Interventional procedures:</strong> Nerve blocks, trigger point injections</li>
                        <li><strong>Surgery:</strong> For specific conditions when identified</li>
                        <li><strong>Lifestyle modifications:</strong> Diet, exercise, stress management</li>
                        <li><strong>Complementary therapies:</strong> Acupuncture, cognitive behavioral therapy, mindfulness</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4">
                      <div class="alert alert-success">
                        <h6>Self-Care Strategies:</h6>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Heat therapy for muscle relaxation</li>
                          <li>Gentle stretching exercises</li>
                          <li>Stress reduction techniques</li>
                          <li>Avoiding trigger foods</li>
                          <li>Proper hydration</li>
                          <li>Sleep hygiene</li>
                          <li>Support groups</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>
                      
                      <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
                        <p class="mb-0">Due to its complex nature, chronic pelvic pain often requires a multidisciplinary approach, involving gynecologists, pain specialists, physical therapists, and mental health professionals.</p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
