    <div class="col-lg-4 mt-4 mt-lg-0">
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <img src="https://pixabay.com/get/gf935c378cc3d20637debf6f3b5b37ce703ea35314de29a03b039cce5f749971ae4fcc0099cc5ac48dfb38758c136478abef653caf3e487578894774827fc6b87_1280.jpg" class="card-img-top" alt="Healthcare consultation">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">When to See a Healthcare Provider</h5>
          
          <div class="alert alert-danger mb-3">
            <h6 class="alert-heading">Seek Immediate Medical Attention If:</h6>
            <ul class="mb-0">
              <li>Severe, sudden pelvic or abdominal pain</li>
              <li>Heavy vaginal bleeding (soaking through a pad/tampon per hour)</li>
              <li>Fever above 101°F (38.3°C) with pelvic pain</li>
              <li>Fainting or severe dizziness</li>
              <li>Sudden or severe changes in vision or severe headache</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <h6>Schedule an Appointment For:</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Irregular periods or changes in your cycle</li>
            <li>Painful periods that interfere with daily activities</li>
            <li>Bleeding between periods</li>
            <li>Painful intercourse</li>
            <li>Unusual vaginal discharge</li>
            <li>Pelvic pain that persists or recurs</li>
            <li>Urinary symptoms (frequency, urgency, burning)</li>
            <li>Vaginal dryness or irritation</li>
            <li>Lumps or masses in the breast or pelvis</li>
            <li>Symptoms that concern you</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6>Regular Check-ups:</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Annual well-woman exam:</strong> Even when you feel well</li>
            <li><strong>Pap tests:</strong> Generally every 3-5 years depending on age and history</li>
            <li><strong>STI screening:</strong> Regularly if sexually active with new or multiple partners</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Preparing for Your Gynecologist Appointment</h5>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Before Your Appointment:</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Track your symptoms:</strong> Note when they occur, severity, triggers</li>
            <li><strong>Track your menstrual cycle:</strong> First day, duration, flow heaviness</li>
            <li><strong>Make a list of medications:</strong> Include prescriptions, over-the-counter, supplements</li>
            <li><strong>Know your medical history:</strong> Previous conditions, surgeries, family history</li>
            <li><strong>Prepare questions:</strong> Write them down to make sure they're addressed</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Questions to Ask:</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>What might be causing my symptoms?</li>
            <li>What tests or evaluations do I need?</li>
            <li>What are my treatment options and their benefits/risks?</li>
            <li>Are there lifestyle changes that might help?</li>
            <li>How urgent is my condition?</li>
            <li>What should I expect in terms of recovery or management?</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">During Your Appointment:</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Be open and honest about your symptoms and concerns</li>
            <li>Don't be embarrassed - gynecologists have seen and heard it all</li>
            <li>Clarify anything you don't understand</li>
            <li>Take notes or bring someone to help remember information</li>
          </ul>
          
          <div class="alert alert-success mt-3">
            <p class="mb-0"><strong>Remember:</strong> You are your own best advocate. If you feel your concerns aren't being addressed, it's okay to seek a second opinion or find a provider you're comfortable with.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Preventive Practices</h5>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">General Gynecological Health</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Maintain good hygiene (gentle cleansing with mild soap and water)</li>
            <li>Avoid douching, which can disrupt vaginal pH</li>
            <li>Wear breathable cotton underwear</li>
            <li>Practice safe sex (condoms help prevent STIs)</li>
            <li>Get regular check-ups and screenings</li>
            <li>Know your normal (what's typical for your body)</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Lifestyle Factors</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Nutrition:</strong> Balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains</li>
            <li><strong>Hydration:</strong> Adequate water intake helps urinary and reproductive health</li>
            <li><strong>Exercise:</strong> Regular physical activity supports overall health</li>
            <li><strong>Weight management:</strong> Helps reduce risk of many gynecological conditions</li>
            <li><strong>Stress management:</strong> Chronic stress can impact hormonal balance</li>
            <li><strong>Smoking cessation:</strong> Smoking increases risk of many reproductive issues</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Pelvic Floor Exercises</h6>
          <p>Regular Kegel exercises strengthen pelvic floor muscles, which can help prevent:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Urinary incontinence</li>
            <li>Pelvic organ prolapse</li>
            <li>Some types of pelvic pain</li>
          </ul>
          
          <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
            <h6 class="alert-heading">How to Do Kegel Exercises:</h6>
            <ol class="mb-0">
              <li>Identify the right muscles (those you use to stop urination midstream)</li>
              <li>Tighten these muscles and hold for 5 seconds</li>
              <li>Relax for 5 seconds</li>
              <li>Repeat 10 times, 3 times daily</li>
              <li>Gradually increase hold time to 10 seconds</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Hormonal Health Throughout Life</h5>
          
          <div class="accordion" id="hormonalHealthAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingAdolescence">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseAdolescence" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseAdolescence">
                  Adolescence
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseAdolescence" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingAdolescence" data-bs-parent="#hormonalHealthAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <ul>
                    <li>Puberty begins with rising estrogen levels</li>
                    <li>Menstrual cycles may be irregular for first few years</li>
                    <li>Common issues: heavy or painful periods, delayed menstruation</li>
                    <li>Focus on: tracking cycles, nutrition, physical activity</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
